\title{CRANE: An Autonomous Research Assistant MCP Server\\for Multi-Source Academic Paper Management}
\author{August Chao\\OpenCode Research Lab}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} MCP, AI agents, research automation, academic workflows, LLM verification

\begin{abstract}
	We present CRANE (Comprehensive Research Automation for Neural Exploration), an autonomous research assistant implemented as a Model Context Protocol (MCP) server. CRANE integrates multi-source academic paper retrieval from four databases (arXiv, OpenAlex, Semantic Scholar, Crossref), metadata normalization with automatic deduplication, and a 3-LLM verification pipeline for AI writing detection. The system supports 28 MCP tools across 7 categories, including paper search, reference management (YAML + BibTeX), task tracking (GitHub Issues), and publication-quality figure generation. CRANE introduces a novel Protected Zones mechanism that preserves verified content during automated paper revision, ensuring data integrity throughout the verification process. We evaluate the system on a 342-test suite with 100\% pass rate and demonstrate its integration with the OpenCode platform. Our approach builds on recent advances in AI agent frameworks for scientific research~\citep{moreno2026ai-agents-hep}, extending them with specialized tools for academic workflows.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

The exponential growth of academic literature presents significant challenges for researchers. With over 2 million papers published annually across major databases, systematic literature review has become increasingly time-consuming. The practical burden is not only volume, but also heterogeneity: preprints, publisher metadata, citation graphs, and supplementary artifacts are distributed across partially overlapping systems with inconsistent schemas and quality controls~\citep{priem2022openalex,lo2020s2orc,hendricks2020crossref}. As a result, researchers frequently spend substantial time reconciling metadata, tracking provenance of claims, and manually validating references before writing can begin.

Traditional tools like Zotero and Mendeley focus primarily on reference management, lacking integrated workflows for multi-source retrieval, quality verification, and automated paper improvement~\citep{zotero2024,mendeley2024}. Discovery-oriented products such as Semantic Scholar and ResearchRabbit improve search and graph exploration but still separate retrieval from manuscript-grounded verification and revision loops~\citep{ammar2018construction,researchrabbit2024}. AI-assisted literature products (e.g., Elicit) improve screening and summarization but commonly assume a human-in-the-loop export pipeline instead of an end-to-end, auditable agentic workflow with explicit control boundaries~\citep{elicit2024,park2023recite}.

Recent work has demonstrated the potential of AI agents in scientific research~\citep{moreno2026ai-agents-hep}, showing that large language models can autonomously execute substantial portions of analysis pipelines. Parallel advances in tool-using LLMs and orchestrated agent frameworks, including ReAct-style planning and role-based collaboration, indicate that robust autonomous workflows are increasingly feasible~\citep{yao2022react,schick2023toolformer,wu2023autogen,qin2023toolllm,langchain2022,crewai2024}. However, existing systems often lack specialized tools for academic workflows, multi-source integration, and quality verification mechanisms. Critically, many systems emphasize generation quality while under-specifying evidence traceability and post-generation integrity.

At the same time, writing-quality concerns in high-stakes academic settings have intensified. Empirical studies on AI-generated text detection and LLM evaluation show that style-level fluency can obscure weak attribution, overclaiming, or unstable reasoning when manuscripts are rapidly revised~\citep{mitchell2023detectgpt,liang2023holistic,zheng2023judging,chang2024survey}. This motivates architectures that jointly optimize discovery, verification, constrained editing, and reproducibility rather than treating these as independent tasks.

We introduce CRANE, an autonomous research assistant that addresses these limitations through an MCP-native systems design, explicit verification layers, and workflow-level reproducibility controls. Beyond providing callable tools, CRANE models research operations as composable, testable services with typed interfaces and explicit state transitions. This design allows the same components to be used interactively by human researchers and programmatically by autonomous agents.

Our contributions are fourfold: (1) We design and implement an autonomous MCP-native research assistant with broad operational coverage (83 tools in the current release lineage), providing a unified interface for search, reference management, verification, and manuscript-quality workflows~\citep{anthropic2024mcp}. (2) We build a multi-source retrieval and normalization pipeline spanning arXiv, OpenAlex, Semantic Scholar, and Crossref, and show that provenance-preserving deduplication can be integrated into an end-to-end artifact lifecycle rather than handled as an external cleanup step. (3) We introduce a three-role LLM verification architecture with Protected Zones, enabling constrained revision where verified citations and critical claims remain integrity-preserving under iterative edits. (4) We provide an evaluation framework that combines software-quality evidence, workflow benchmarks, baseline comparisons, and ablation-style analysis, supported by a large automated validation suite (1,432 passing tests in the reported run).

The rest of this paper is organized as follows. Section~\ref{sec:related_work} situates CRANE within AI agent frameworks, academic discovery systems, MCP infrastructure, and automated writing support. Section~\ref{sec:architecture} details the system architecture, service boundaries, dataflow, workspace lifecycle, and version management strategy. Section~\ref{sec:pipeline} describes the 3-LLM verification pipeline, prompt design, and failure handling. Section~\ref{sec:implementation} documents implementation and deployment details. Section~\ref{sec:empirical_evaluation} reports empirical findings, including testing outcomes, benchmark behaviors, and ablations. Section~\ref{sec:limitations} discusses limitations, threats to validity, responsible use, and future directions. Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes.

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related_work}

\subsection{AI Agent Frameworks}

The application of AI agents to scientific research has gained significant attention. \citet{moreno2026ai-agents-hep} demonstrated that AI agents can autonomously perform experimental high-energy physics analyses, including event selection, background estimation, and paper drafting. Their findings suggest that code-executing agents can cover substantial portions of end-to-end scientific workflows when coupled with reliable tools and domain constraints.

In the broader agent literature, tool-use and planning paradigms have evolved from prompt-only interaction toward explicit reasoning-action loops and multi-agent role assignment. \citet{yao2022react} propose interleaving reasoning traces with external actions; \citet{schick2023toolformer} show self-supervised adaptation for API use; and \citet{wu2023autogen} present conversation-driven multi-agent coordination. Framework ecosystems such as LangChain and CrewAI package these patterns for practical deployment~\citep{langchain2022,crewai2024}. Surveys further indicate that robust autonomous behavior depends less on model scale alone and more on disciplined orchestration, tool grounding, and verification policies~\citep{qin2023toolllm,raschka2025llm-arch-comparison}.

CRANE differs from general agent frameworks in three ways. First, it is domain-specific to academic workflows rather than general task automation. Second, it co-designs retrieval and verification layers, avoiding late-stage patching of citation issues. Third, it introduces edit-time integrity constraints (Protected Zones) as first-class pipeline artifacts.

\subsection{Academic Search and Discovery Tools}

The modern scholarly infrastructure includes discovery engines (Semantic Scholar), open metadata graphs (OpenAlex), citation corpora (S2ORC), and persistent identifier services (Crossref)~\citep{ammar2018construction,priem2022openalex,lo2020s2orc,hendricks2020crossref}. These systems provide strong coverage and metadata depth, but researchers still face practical integration costs when moving from discovery to manuscript-ready evidence chains.

Commercial and community products provide partial solutions. Elicit supports question-centric literature exploration and synthesis; ResearchRabbit emphasizes citation-network navigation; Zotero and Mendeley provide mature personal library management~\citep{elicit2024,researchrabbit2024,zotero2024,mendeley2024}. None of these tools natively implement an autonomous, end-to-end loop that includes (i) multi-source ingestion, (ii) normalized reference persistence in both human-readable and citation-ready formats, (iii) manuscript citation checks, and (iv) constrained automated revision.

Recent research on retrieval-augmented generation and citation-aware QA reinforces this gap. While retrieval mechanisms improve factual grounding, practical citation integrity remains sensitive to source quality, chunking strategy, and rewrite behavior~\citep{lewis2020rag,guu2020retrieval,cohan2020specter,park2023recite}. CRANE addresses this by linking reference management and verification directly into the manuscript-editing pipeline.

\subsection{MCP Ecosystem and Tool Interoperability}

The Model Context Protocol (MCP) provides a standardized interaction model between LLM applications and external tools~\citep{anthropic2024mcp}. By reducing tool-invocation heterogeneity, MCP enables reusable interfaces across agent runtimes, improving portability and operational consistency. CRANE leverages MCP to expose research functionality as callable tools, enabling integration with OpenCode and other MCP-compatible platforms while preserving stateless server semantics at the transport layer.

From a software architecture perspective, protocol-level interoperability is necessary but not sufficient. End-to-end reliability additionally depends on stable service contracts, schema versioning, and graceful handling of external API variance~\citep{bass2021software,fowler2002patterns}. CRANE therefore combines MCP exposure with an internal service layer and provider abstraction that isolate source-specific failures from user-facing workflows.

\subsection{Automated Writing Systems and Verification}

LLM-assisted writing systems increasingly support drafting, rewriting, and stylistic adaptation, but high-stakes scientific manuscripts require stronger guarantees on evidence traceability and claim consistency~\citep{bommasani2021foundation,brown2020gpt3,ouyang2022instructgpt}. Evaluation studies show that fluent generations can still include unsupported claims, inconsistent framing, or unstable citation behavior under iterative edits~\citep{liang2023holistic,zheng2023judging,chang2024survey}.

AI writing detection research offers complementary signals. Surface-level detectors can identify repetitive lexical artifacts, while structure-aware and discourse-aware methods examine paragraph regularity and argument stance~\citep{mitchell2023detectgpt,gehrmann2019gltr,sadasivan2023detecting}. However, detectors alone do not prevent integrity regressions during rewriting. CRANE's 3-LLM architecture combines detection with constrained editing and re-verification, turning detection signals into actionable editorial controls.

Table~\ref{tab:rw_comparison} compares CRANE with representative systems. The goal is not to claim strict superiority in every function but to highlight design intent: CRANE prioritizes workflow completeness and verification-aware automation for research production settings.

