\section{System Architecture}
\label{sec:architecture}

\subsection{Architectural Overview and Design Principles}

CRANE follows a layered architecture: MCP tool interface \(\rightarrow\) domain service layer \(\rightarrow\) provider adapters \(\rightarrow\) external systems (academic APIs, local workspace, GitHub). The design is guided by four principles: (i) \emph{interface uniformity} for autonomous agents, (ii) \emph{explicit provenance} for research artifacts, (iii) \emph{replaceable providers} for source resilience, and (iv) \emph{verification-first workflows} for manuscript integrity.

This organization separates concerns between protocol compatibility and domain logic. MCP tools provide stable entry points, while service objects implement policy and orchestration. Provider adapters isolate source-specific protocol differences and rate-limit behavior. Persistent artifacts are maintained in text-first formats (YAML, BibTeX, Markdown) to support version control, reviewability, and reproducibility.

To make the architecture operationally precise, we define the core formal objects used across orchestration and verification. Let
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{T} = \{t_1, t_2, \ldots, t_n\}
\end{equation}
denote the MCP tool set, where each $t_i$ is a callable tool with typed input-output contracts. For citation checking, we define
\begin{equation}
V(c, \mathcal{R}) \rightarrow \{\texttt{valid},\texttt{invalid}\},
\end{equation}
where $c$ is a citation key extracted from manuscript text and $\mathcal{R}$ is the reference set stored in YAML/BibTeX artifacts. The three-role verification pipeline is modeled as function composition,
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P} = \mathrm{LLM}_\mathrm{C} \circ \mathrm{LLM}_\mathrm{B} \circ \mathrm{LLM}_\mathrm{A},
\end{equation}
with Auditor outputs feeding Detector analysis and then constrained Editor revision. Finally, Protected Zones are represented as
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{Z} = \{z_1, z_2, \ldots, z_m\},\quad z_j=(\text{span}_j, h_j),
\end{equation}
where each zone $z_j$ binds a protected span to a checksum hash $h_j$ used for integrity checks during rewrite validation.

\subsection{MCP Server Design}

CRANE is implemented as an MCP server with tools organized into coherent capability groups (83 tools in the current release lineage, with 28 core tools in the initial implementation cohort):

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{ll}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Category}       & \textbf{Tools}                                              \\
		\midrule
		Project Management      & init\_research, get\_project\_info                          \\
		Paper Search            & search\_papers, download\_paper, read\_paper                \\
		Reference Management    & add\_reference, list\_references, get\_reference, ...       \\
		Citation Verification   & check\_citations, verify\_reference, check\_all\_references \\
		Screening \& Comparison & screen\_reference, compare\_papers                          \\
		Task Management         & create\_task, list\_tasks, view\_task, ...                  \\
		Workflow                & run\_pipeline, workspace\_status                            \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
	\caption{CRANE MCP Tools by Category}
	\label{tab:tools}
\end{table}

Each tool exposes narrow, composable operations rather than monolithic ``do everything'' commands. This enables orchestration pipelines that remain inspectable, resumable, and testable. For example, literature intake can be decomposed into search, metadata verification, screening, and reference insertion, with each step producing intermediate artifacts that can be audited.

\subsection{Service Layer Architecture}

The service layer provides business logic independent of the MCP interface and is structured around domain boundaries:

\begin{itemize}
	\item \texttt{PaperService}: arXiv search, download, and text extraction
	\item \texttt{ReferenceService}: YAML + BibTeX CRUD operations
	\item \texttt{TaskService}: GitHub Issues management
	\item \texttt{CitationService}: Citation verification and validation
	\item \texttt{MetadataService}: Metadata normalization and deduplication
	\item \texttt{ScreeningService}: Paper screening and comparison
	\item \texttt{FigureGenerator}: Publication-quality figure generation
	\item \texttt{JournalRecommender}: Journal recommendation with OpenAlex + SJR
\end{itemize}

Service boundaries are intentionally strict. Cross-service calls are mediated through typed data models, which limits hidden coupling and improves testability. For example, reference normalization does not mutate manuscript files directly; instead, it emits validated records that downstream citation checks consume.

\subsection{Dataflow and Orchestration Across Services}

Figure~\ref{fig:dataflow} illustrates the end-to-end research dataflow. A user request enters via MCP, is dispatched to orchestrator logic, and then activates provider-specific retrieval. Retrieved metadata are normalized and deduplicated before persisting to workspace storage. Verification and writing modules consume these artifacts to produce manuscript-oriented outputs (reports, revised sections, citation diagnostics).

