		\draw[arrow] (mcp) -- (semantic);
	\end{tikzpicture}
	\caption{Multi-Source Provider Architecture}
	\label{fig:providers}
\end{figure}

Provider abstraction improves robustness in two ways. First, each provider encapsulates source-specific query syntax, pagination, and retry behavior, allowing the orchestrator to execute fallback strategies without duplicating logic. Second, provider outputs are mapped into a canonical metadata schema, so downstream services can operate independently of source idiosyncrasies.

\subsection{Workspace Management and Artifact Lifecycle}

CRANE adopts a workspace-centric model in which all research artifacts are represented as versionable files. References are stored as structured YAML records and synchronized BibTeX entries; task state is mirrored via GitHub issues; manuscript diagnostics are emitted as markdown or YAML reports. This text-first approach aligns with reproducible research practices and supports collaboration through standard source-control workflows.

A typical lifecycle comprises: (i) initialization of project labels/milestones, (ii) literature intake and screening, (iii) citation graph and coverage analysis, (iv) manuscript verification and revision planning, and (v) submission-readiness checks. By persisting intermediate outputs, CRANE allows interrupted workflows to resume without hidden state reconstruction.

\subsection{Version Management Architecture}

Long-horizon research projects require toolchain stability under continuous updates. CRANE therefore includes explicit version management pathways: update checks, controlled upgrade routines with backup, rollback support, and migration tracking. Architecturally, version operations are isolated from core research services to reduce blast radius. Upgrade actions are treated as managed workflows with pre/post verification gates (dependency sync, test execution, migration status checks), while rollback paths prioritize restoration of known-good states.

This architecture supports two practical needs in academic production environments: reproducibility for submitted results and maintainability for evolving automation stacks.

\section{3-LLM Verification Pipeline}
\label{sec:pipeline}

\subsection{Architecture Overview}

The verification pipeline implements a 3-LLM architecture with orthogonal cognitive modes. Rather than assigning all responsibilities to one generalist model, CRANE decomposes verification into independent objectives to reduce mode collapse and prompt interference:

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{lll}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Role}    & \textbf{Cognitive Mode} & \textbf{Responsibility}                     \\
		\midrule
		LLM-A (Auditor)  & Precise, conservative   & Data traceability, citation verification    \\
		LLM-B (Detector) & Pattern-sensitive       & AI writing fingerprint detection (L1/L2/L3) \\
		LLM-C (Editor)   & Creative, domain-expert & Constrained rewriting with Protected Zones  \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
	\caption{3-LLM Role Definitions}
	\label{tab:roles}
\end{table}

The interaction contract between roles is explicit. LLM-A produces evidence-ledger outputs and citation checks; LLM-B consumes manuscript text and emits layered risk signals; LLM-C receives both plus protected-span constraints and proposes revisions. A final re-verification pass by LLM-A acts as a consistency gate before acceptance.

\subsection{Three-Layer AI Detection}

AI writing detection operates across three layers:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{L1 (Surface)}: Vocabulary patterns, hedging phrases, mechanical connectors
	\item \textbf{L2 (Structural)}: Paragraph symmetry, sentence variety, section flow
	\item \textbf{L3 (Intellectual)}: Stance detection, insight depth, tension assessment
\end{enumerate}

This layered decomposition allows heterogeneous error modes to be surfaced separately. For instance, a section can have low L1 risk (natural lexical variation) but elevated L3 risk (insufficiently grounded argument structure). This is important for research writing, where stylistic fluency alone is a weak proxy for scholarly rigor.

\subsection{Prompt Engineering and Role-Specific Instruction Design}

Prompt design in CRANE emphasizes role isolation, structured outputs, and fail-safe defaults. Each role receives a bounded prompt with: (i) objective definition, (ii) allowed operations, (iii) required output schema, and (iv) refusal conditions. The Auditor role is conservative by design and is instructed to prefer ``uncertain'' over unsupported verification. The Detector role is calibrated to report evidence snippets, not only binary labels. The Editor role receives explicit rewrite constraints and must preserve protected spans exactly.

A practical design choice is to keep role prompts short but schema-rich. Excessive instruction length increases brittleness under iterative revisions; schema richness improves machine-checkable outputs for downstream gates. The orchestrator enforces response contracts using parsing and validation rules before any rewrite is committed.

\subsection{Protected Zones Mechanism}

The Protected Zones mechanism preserves verified content during automated revision:

\begin{itemize}
	\item Verified citations become protected zones with checksums
	\item Editors cannot modify protected content
	\item Zones are stored in YAML for queryability and git-friendliness
	\item Automatic propagation through verification pipeline
\end{itemize}

Operationally, each protected zone records source location, semantic type (e.g., citation key, numerical claim, definition), hash signature, and revision policy. During editing, candidate outputs are diffed against protected spans; if a protected token is altered without authorization, the candidate is rejected and either repaired automatically or routed for human review.

This mechanism is especially valuable for iterative revision settings where stylistic rewrites can inadvertently alter citation anchors, numeric values, or formal definitions. By elevating protected spans to first-class constraints, CRANE bridges the gap between language generation flexibility and scientific-document integrity.

\subsection{Role-Level Performance Characterization}

Table~\ref{tab:pipeline_perf} summarizes role-level operational behavior measured in development workflows. To avoid overclaiming, we report qualitative and range-based characteristics rather than hardware-specific point estimates.

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{llll}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Role}  & \textbf{Primary Signal}       & \textbf{Typical Latency Class} & \textbf{Common Failure Trigger}              \\
		\midrule
		LLM-A Auditor  & Evidence consistency          & interactive (seconds)          & ambiguous or missing metadata                \\
		LLM-B Detector & Layered writing risk          & interactive (seconds)          & domain-shifted writing style                 \\
		LLM-C Editor   & Constraint-preserving rewrite & interactive-to-batch           & conflicting style vs. protection constraints \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
	\caption{Role-level performance characterization of the 3-LLM pipeline.}
	\label{tab:pipeline_perf}
\end{table}

\subsection{Failure Mode Analysis and Mitigation}

We identify four recurrent failure modes. \textbf{(F1) Citation drift}: rewritten text weakens citation-claim alignment even when keys remain intact. \textbf{Mitigation}: Auditor re-verification and claim-level checks. \textbf{(F2) Over-normalization}: editor homogenizes voice and removes disciplinary nuance. \textbf{Mitigation}: style constraints with section-specific exemptions. \textbf{(F3) False positive detection}: detector overflags concise technical prose as AI-like. \textbf{Mitigation}: multi-layer evidence requirements and confidence bucketing. \textbf{(F4) Constraint deadlock}: heavy protected zones leave insufficient editable text. \textbf{Mitigation}: progressive relaxation policies requiring explicit human authorization.

\begin{figure}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[
			box/.style={rectangle, draw, minimum width=3cm, minimum height=0.8cm, text centered},
			arrow/.style={thick,->,>=stealth}
		]
		\node[box] (audit) at (0,0) {LLM-A: AUDIT};
		\node[box] (detect) at (0,-1.2) {LLM-B: DETECTION};
		\node[box] (edit) at (0,-2.4) {LLM-C: EDITING};
		\node[box] (verify) at (0,-3.6) {LLM-A: RE-VERIFY};
		\node[box] (report) at (0,-4.8) {REPORT};

		\draw[arrow] (audit) -- (detect);
		\draw[arrow] (detect) -- (edit);
