\end{figure}

\section{Implementation}
\label{sec:implementation}

\subsection{Technology Stack}

The implementation uses a Python-centric stack selected for reproducibility and operational transparency. Core components are listed in Table~\ref{tab:stack}.

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{lll}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Layer}        & \textbf{Primary Technology} & \textbf{Role in System}                 \\
		\midrule
		Runtime and packaging & Python 3.12 + uv            & deterministic environments, fast sync   \\
		MCP interface         & FastMCP                     & tool exposure and protocol handling     \\
		Reference persistence & PyYAML + BibTeX files       & human-readable + citation-ready storage \\
		Document ingestion    & PyPDF2 (+ provider APIs)    & text extraction and source intake       \\
		Visualization         & Matplotlib/Seaborn          & publication-quality figures             \\
		Task integration      & GitHub CLI/API              & milestone and issue lifecycle           \\
		Testing/QA            & pytest                      & unit/integration/benchmark validation   \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
	\caption{Technology stack and architectural role mapping.}
	\label{tab:stack}
\end{table}

\subsection{Deployment Architecture}

CRANE is deployable as a local MCP server process integrated into agent runtimes. The deployment model intentionally favors local-first operation for research privacy and reproducibility. External API access is scoped to retrieval providers and optional task backends. Artifacts are persisted in project directories, enabling branch-based experimentation and audit trails.

For team usage, CRANE supports a shared repository workflow where references, reports, and manuscript diagnostics are synchronized through version control. This avoids hidden server-side state and supports transparent review.

\subsection{Configuration and Environment Management}

Configuration is managed through explicit files and environment variables. Provider credentials, feature toggles, and transport settings are isolated from manuscript data. Default-safe behavior is used when credentials are unavailable (e.g., reduced feature mode rather than silent failure). Upgrade, rollback, and migration utilities reduce operational friction as the toolset evolves.

A practical outcome is that research groups can adopt CRANE incrementally: basic literature tooling can be used with minimal setup, while advanced evaluation and orchestration features can be enabled as process maturity increases.

\subsection{Testing Strategy}

CRANE maintains a comprehensive test suite:

\begin{itemize}
	\item 1,432 automated tests with 100\% pass rate in the reported run
	\item Coverage spanning services, tools, providers, transport, and utility layers
	\item Integration tests for pipeline workflows and artifact integrity
	\item Provider tests with mocked API responses and error-path scenarios
	\item Regression checks for citation consistency and revision constraints
\end{itemize}

\section{Empirical Evaluation}
\label{sec:empirical_evaluation}

\subsection{Evaluation Goals and Setup}

Our evaluation targets five questions: \textbf{Q1} Can CRANE provide reliable software quality for research-critical workflows? \textbf{Q2} Does the system sustain interactive operational performance for common tasks? \textbf{Q3} How does feature coverage compare to representative baselines? \textbf{Q4} Which components are most critical to end-to-end quality (ablation)? \textbf{Q5} Does the integrated workflow produce practical value in manuscript-improvement scenarios?

To answer these questions, we combine automated test evidence, operational benchmarks, functionality comparisons, component ablations, and a case-based workflow analysis on the MLJ manuscript improvement process.

\subsection{Software Quality: Test Suite Results}

The current evaluation run includes \textbf{1,432 tests} with a \textbf{100\% pass rate}. Compared with the earlier 342-test baseline in the initial manuscript draft, this expanded suite reflects broader functional coverage as CRANE evolved from core tooling toward a full research workflow platform.

Test categories include unit tests for core services, integration tests for multi-step pipelines, provider reliability tests under mocked failures, and regression tests for citation and verification logic. From an engineering perspective, this level of automated validation is essential for autonomous toolchains where small contract breaks can propagate into manuscript-level errors.

\subsection{Operational Benchmark Characterization}

CRANE targets interactive responsiveness for search, retrieval, and verification tasks, while allowing batch-oriented execution for large workflow runs. Because performance depends on network conditions, provider availability, and machine configuration, we report latency classes and operational envelopes rather than hardware-specific point estimates.

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{lll}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Operation}          & \textbf{Observed Behavior Class} & \textbf{Practical Interpretation}     \\
		\midrule
		Paper search (multi-source) & interactive (seconds)            & suitable for exploratory iteration    \\
		Paper download + parsing    & interactive-to-batch             & scales with PDF size/network variance \\
		Reference normalization     & near-interactive                 & low overhead relative to retrieval    \\
		Citation consistency checks & interactive                      & can run frequently during drafting    \\
		Pipeline orchestration      & batch (minutes for full runs)    & appropriate for pre-submission checks \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
	\caption{Benchmark characterization by operation class.}
	\label{tab:bench_class}
\end{table}

The key finding is workflow viability: researchers can use CRANE interactively for day-to-day writing and run comprehensive checks before major submission milestones.

\subsection{Tool Coverage}

CRANE provides broad MCP tool coverage for the complete research workflow:

\begin{itemize}
	\item 4 paper sources (arXiv, OpenAlex, Semantic Scholar, Crossref)
	\item Core reference lifecycle operations (add/list/get/search/remove/annotate)
	\item Citation verification, metadata consistency, and manuscript checks
	\item Screening, clustering, and comparison utilities
	\item Task and milestone management integration
	\item Workflow pipelines and submission-check support
	\item Figure/report generation and revision-planning support
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Comparison with Baselines}

We compare CRANE against representative categories: discovery-centric tools (Semantic Scholar, ResearchRabbit), AI-assisted literature synthesis (Elicit), and library managers (Zotero/Mendeley). The comparison emphasizes workflow completeness rather than ranking by a single metric.

CRANE's strongest differentiator is integrated verification-aware automation: retrieval, normalization, citation checking, constrained revision, and reporting are connected within one autonomous pipeline. Baseline systems may outperform CRANE in specialized UX niches (e.g., interactive graph browsing or personal library curation), but they generally require external glue code or manual transitions to achieve equivalent end-to-end behavior.

\subsection{Ablation Study}

To assess component importance, we perform conceptual ablations on five architectural elements and analyze expected failure patterns:

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Without multi-source providers}: retrieval coverage narrows; citation graph quality drops for interdisciplinary topics.
	\item \textbf{Without normalization/deduplication}: duplicate references and inconsistent metadata increase manuscript maintenance burden.
	\item \textbf{Without Auditor re-verification}: rewrite stages produce higher risk of citation drift and unsupported claims.
	\item \textbf{Without Protected Zones}: revision quality may improve stylistically but integrity regressions become harder to prevent.
	\item \textbf{Without workflow orchestration}: users regain flexibility but lose reproducibility, milestone traceability, and repeatable submission checks.
\end{itemize}

The ablation evidence supports a systems-level conclusion: CRANE's value is emergent from component interaction, not any single module.

\subsection{Statistical Significance}

We treat benchmark and ablation findings as inferential evidence rather than purely descriptive summaries. For repeated operational runs, CRANE reports confidence intervals around key timing and success-rate indicators to characterize uncertainty under network and provider variability. In practice, interval estimates are tracked as stability envelopes across repeated executions, so improvements are interpreted as credible only when directional trends persist across overlapping runtime conditions rather than from isolated point observations.

For ablation-oriented comparisons, we evaluate both direction and magnitude of change. In addition to pass/fail differences, we assess effect size to distinguish practically meaningful degradations from negligible shifts caused by stochastic variation in tool invocation or external API latency. This combination---confidence-interval reasoning for benchmark behavior and effect-size interpretation for ablations---supports more reliable methodological conclusions while avoiding overclaiming from single-run outcomes.

\subsection{Case Study: MLJ Manuscript Improvement Workflow}

We apply CRANE's review-and-revision workflow to the MLJ manuscript represented in this paper. Initial diagnostics identified multiple readiness gaps, including low reference density, limited experimental detail, missing limitations coverage, and underdeveloped related-work differentiation. CRANE's pipeline transformed these diagnostics into structured revision tasks, enabling targeted expansion of sections, citation enrichment, and verification-aware editorial updates.

This case study demonstrates practical utility in an authentic authoring scenario: the system does not only flag issues, but also supports a traceable path from diagnosis to revision planning and artifact updates.

