\section{Limitations and Future Work}
\label{sec:limitations}

Despite promising results, CRANE has several limitations. First, while the architecture is domain-extensible, current optimization emphasizes computer science and adjacent technical domains. Domain transfer to highly regulated fields (e.g., clinical medicine, legal scholarship) requires additional ontology alignment, stricter compliance checks, and stronger source-governance policies. Second, CRANE currently prioritizes asynchronous, file-centric collaboration over real-time collaborative editing. This design improves traceability but may feel less fluid for teams expecting synchronous co-authoring experiences.

Third, provider dependence remains a practical constraint. External API policies, rate limits, and metadata quality vary over time; although provider abstraction mitigates disruption, it cannot eliminate upstream volatility. Fourth, LLM-based verification still inherits model-specific biases and calibration issues. Detector signals may overgeneralize across writing styles, especially in cross-lingual or highly mathematical manuscripts.

\subsection{Threats to Validity}

Internal validity may be affected by implementation coupling between service contracts and test assumptions; strong pass rates do not guarantee absence of uncaptured edge cases. Construct validity is constrained by available evaluation proxies: benchmark classes and workflow outcomes reflect operational usefulness but do not fully measure scientific impact quality. External validity is limited because baseline comparisons are function-oriented and do not uniformly account for differences in product scope, target users, and deployment models.

\subsection{Responsible Use Considerations}

CRANE is designed as an assistant for responsible scholarship, not a replacement for expert judgment. We recommend explicit human oversight for claim interpretation, methodological framing, and ethical compliance. Automated rewriting should be constrained by transparent policies (e.g., Protected Zones) and paired with provenance logging. Users should disclose AI assistance according to venue-specific requirements and avoid using automation to mask uncertainty or inflate contribution claims.

\subsection{Future Work Roadmap}

We plan four development tracks. \textbf{(R1) Domain expansion:} add domain packs and validation templates for medicine, social science, and law. \textbf{(R2) Collaboration:} introduce real-time shared sessions and role-aware review channels while preserving audit trails. \textbf{(R3) Verification depth:} extend claim-level evidence modeling with stronger contradiction detection and citation-quality scoring. \textbf{(R4) Evaluation rigor:} conduct larger-scale user studies with controlled comparisons on time-to-submission, revision quality, and reviewer outcomes.

Collectively, these directions move CRANE from a robust engineering platform toward a broader research-infrastructure layer for trustworthy scholarly automation.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

CRANE provides a comprehensive autonomous research assistant through MCP integration. The system demonstrates how AI agents can be enhanced with specialized tools for academic workflows, and how protocol-level interoperability can be combined with verification-aware architecture for practical manuscript production. Building on recent work demonstrating AI agents' capability in scientific research~\citep{moreno2026ai-agents-hep}, CRANE extends these capabilities with specialized academic tools, multi-source integration, and quality verification mechanisms.

The core technical message of this paper is architectural: reliable research automation requires co-design across retrieval, normalization, verification, and constrained revision. CRANE operationalizes this through (i) an MCP-native interface, (ii) provider-based multi-source ingestion, (iii) explicit workspace artifacts for reproducibility, and (iv) a 3-LLM pipeline with Protected Zones that protects validated content during iterative editing.

Empirically, the platform demonstrates strong engineering maturity and workflow viability. The current implementation lineage exposes broad tool coverage (83 MCP tools), and our reported validation run includes 1,432 automated tests with full pass status. Evaluation results indicate that CRANE supports interactive research operations for common tasks while enabling deeper pre-submission checks in batch workflows. Baseline comparisons and ablation analysis suggest that system-level integration---rather than isolated features---drives practical value.

From a research-practice perspective, CRANE contributes a replicable framework for integrating autonomous agents into high-stakes academic pipelines without abandoning traceability. The MLJ manuscript case illustrates how the platform can convert diagnostic findings into structured revisions, narrowing the gap between ``issue detection'' and ``submission-ready improvement.''

Future work includes:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Integration with additional paper sources (e.g., PubMed, IEEE Xplore) and domain-specific metadata validators
	\item Enhanced AI writing and claim-verification modules with stronger calibration and contradiction reasoning
	\item Real-time, multi-user collaboration modes with provenance-preserving conflict resolution
	\item Larger-scale empirical studies on researcher productivity, revision quality, and downstream review outcomes
	\item Expanded governance tooling for responsible use, disclosure, and venue-specific compliance
\end{itemize}

We believe these directions can help establish a new class of trustworthy research assistants: systems that accelerate scholarly work while preserving the evidentiary and methodological standards expected by Q1 venues.

